 manifestations of the same phenomenon – intimacy. As forms of communication, they are subject to a historical transformation that differentiates them as distinct models of life. This study examines that long-term transformation using medieval and early modern versions of Virgil’s Aeneid.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aAntike. 4aLiebe. 4aRezeption. 4aVergil. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aVirgil.  aantiquity.  alove.  areception.1 aMüller, Felix Florian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2023 Part 1z978311117578208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2023z9783111318110oZDB-23-DGD0 cEPUBz97831106512630 cprintz978311065114040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311065260440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110652604423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110652604/original  a978-3-11-117578-2  DG Plus DeG Package 2023 Part 1b2023  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGDb2023  aZDB-23-DGGb2023